Guilt-ridden Mpumalanga premier, Refilwe
Mtshweni-Tsipane has paid a fine for defying Covid-19 regulations at the Vosman
police station in Emalahleni today. This is after she was spotted without
wearing a mask at a funeral service of the late Minister in Presidency,
Jackson Mthembu on Sunday. The public lashed her on social media,
stating that it was irresponsible for her to act in such a manner at a funeral
service of a Covid-19 victim. Mtshweni-Tsipane was seen waving to the people
and further went to hug a police officer. In a video circulating on social
media, deputy president David Mabuza, signaled out Tsipane to wear her mask after
delivering her speech however she continued to hold it. Mtshweni-Tsipane said she has noted
social media and media reports revealing moments where she was walking around
without a mask. "I have since reflected deeply on
this momentarily lapse, which I regret profusely. I wish to take this
opportunity once again apologise to His Excellency, President Cyril Ramaphosa,
the Deputy President of the Republic Mr. David Mabuza, the Mthembu family, the
people of Mpumalanga and the rest of the country, " she said She further said she has written a letter
to the president, Ramaphosa expressing her regret of the situation. "To further demonstrate my remorse,
I have bought 1000 masks that will be distributed in Emalahleni as part of
public education and awareness campaign to demonstrate the serious nature of
COVID-19. I wish to take this opportunity to express my condolences to all the
families who have lost their loved ones to the pandemic. I also wish those who
are currently struggling with the virus a speedy recovery, ",she said. Mtshweni-Tsipane said she has decided to
go into isolation for 14 days.